I'm checking the [story for this](https://www.chromatic.com/test?appId=624de63c6aacee003aa84340&id=65a6d218d8ad858d95e67357), and it does feel a little weird to me to be stuffing an alert element inside a table

I do get the point of only rendering the fallback text if there is no error, but I wonder if it might be better to update the rendering condition above, too:

```tsx
// Above the table
{error && <ErrorAlert error={error} />}

// Inside the table
<TableBody>
  {isLoading && <TableLoader />}
  {/**
   * Decouple mapping from any booleans to make sure state doesn't get
   * unloaded in weird edge cases
  */}
  {apps?.map((app) => <OAuth2AppRow key={app.id} app={app} />)}
  {app?.length === 0 && (
    <TableRow>
      <TableCell colSpan={999}>
        <div css={{ textAlign: "center" }}>
          No OAuth2 applications have been configured.
         </div>
      </TableCell>
    </TableRow>
  )}
</TableBody>
```
Here's [an article on error-handling strategies in React Query](https://tkdodo.eu/blog/react-query-error-handling) I use all the time. My main concern is that if there is an error (even during a minor background refetch), the UI immediately hides the fact that we have no applications

[The Chromatic tests](https://www.chromatic.com/test?appId=630513346a8e284ae244d415&id=63cda8c7ca2f3db4f73babaf) shows that force re-rendering doesn't work anymore. The story focuses the button, emits a "force re-render" event and expects the button to loose focus, but it doesn't.

I wonder if that is a bug in this code here. I _think_ that it could be fixed if you unmounted the `storybookApp` from the `map` instead of from the parameter. So something like this (untested):
```suggestion
function teardown(
  canvasElement: VueRenderer['canvasElement']
) {
  if(!map.has(canvasElement)){
    return;
  }
  const { vueApp } = map.get(canvasElement);
  vueApp.unmount();
  map.delete(canvasElement);
}
```

